# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: interactive-proofs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:interactive-proofs/arthur-merlin-protocol] In computational complexity theory, an **Arthur–Merlin protocol**, introduced by Babai (1985), is an interactive proof system in which the verifier's coin tosses are constrained to be public (i.e. known to the prover too).
[src:interactive-proofs/arthur-merlin-protocol] Goldwasser & Sipser (1986) proved that all (formal) languages with interactive proofs of arbitrary length with private coins also have interactive proofs with public coins.
[src:interactive-proofs/arthur-merlin-protocol] Given two participants in the protocol called Arthur and Merlin respectively, the basic assumption is that Arthur is a standard computer (or verifier) equipped with a random number generating device, while Merlin is effectively an oracle with infinite computational power (also known as a prover).
[src:interactive-proofs/arthur-merlin-protocol] However, Merlin is not necessarily honest, so Arthur must analyze the information provided by Merlin in response to Arthur's queries and decide the problem itself.
[src:interactive-proofs/arthur-merlin-protocol] A problem is considered to be solvable by this protocol if whenever the answer is "yes", Merlin has some series of responses which will cause Arthur to accept at least 2⁄3 of the time, and if whenever the answer is "no", Arthur will never accept more than 1⁄3 of the time.
[src:interactive-proofs/arthur-merlin-protocol] Thus, Arthur acts as a probabilistic polynomial-time verifier, assuming it is allotted polynomial time to make its decisions and queries.
[src:interactive-proofs/arthur-merlin-protocol] The simplest such protocol is the 1-message protocol where Merlin sends Arthur a message, and then Arthur decides whether to accept or not by running a probabilistic polynomial time computation.
[src:interactive-proofs/arthur-merlin-protocol] Informally, a language *L* is in **MA** if for all strings in the language, there is a polynomial sized proof that Merlin can send Arthur to convince him of this fact with high probability, and for all strings not in the language there is no proof that convinces Arthur with high probability.
[src:interactive-proofs/arthur-merlin-protocol] Formally, the complexity class **MA** is the set of decision problems that can be decided in polynomial time by an Arthur–Merlin protocol where Merlin's only move precedes any computation by Arthur.
[src:interactive-proofs/arthur-merlin-protocol] To compare this with the informal definition above, *z* is the purported proof from Merlin (whose size is bounded by a polynomial) and *y* is the random string that Arthur uses, which is also polynomially bounded.
[src:interactive-proofs/arthur-merlin-protocol] The complexity class **AM** (or **AM[2]**) is the set of decision problems that can be decided in polynomial time by an Arthur–Merlin protocol with two messages.
[src:interactive-proofs/arthur-merlin-protocol] There is only one query/response pair: Arthur tosses some random coins and sends the outcome of *all* his coin tosses to Merlin, Merlin responds with a purported proof, and Arthur deterministically verifies the proof.
[src:interactive-proofs/arthur-merlin-protocol] In this protocol, Arthur is only allowed to send outcomes of coin tosses to Merlin, and in the final stage Arthur must decide whether to accept or reject using only his previously generated random coin flips and Merlin's message.
[src:interactive-proofs/arthur-merlin-protocol] As above, *z* is the alleged proof from Merlin (whose size is bounded by a polynomial) and *y* is the random string that Arthur uses, which is also polynomially bounded.
[src:interactive-proofs/arthur-merlin-protocol] The complexity class **AM[*k*]** is the set of problems that can be decided in polynomial time, with *k* queries and responses.
[src:interactive-proofs/arthur-merlin-protocol] **AM[3]** would start with one message from Merlin to Arthur, then a message from Arthur to Merlin and then finally a message from Merlin to Arthur.
[src:interactive-proofs/arthur-merlin-protocol] The last message should always be from Merlin to Arthur, since it never helps for Arthur to send a message to Merlin after deciding his answer.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In computational complexity theory, an **interactive proof system** is an abstract machine that models computation as the exchange of messages between two parties: a *prover* and a *verifier*.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The parties interact by exchanging messages in order to ascertain whether a given string belongs to a language or not.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The prover is assumed to possess unlimited computational resources but cannot be trusted, while the verifier has bounded computation power but is assumed to be always honest.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Messages are sent between the verifier and prover until the verifier has an answer to the problem and has "convinced" itself that it is correct.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The specific nature of the system, and so the complexity class of languages it can recognize, depends on what sort of bounds are put on the verifier, as well as what abilities it is given—for example, most interactive proof systems depend critically on the verifier's ability to make random choices.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] It also depends on the nature of the messages exchanged—how many and what they can contain.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Interactive proof systems have been found to have some important implications for traditional complexity classes defined using only one machine.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The main complexity classes describing interactive proof systems are **AM** and **IP**.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Every interactive proof system defines a formal language of strings.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Often an interactive proof system is designed with the *intention* of being a system for a particular language L .
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] **Soundness** of the proof system refers to the property that no prover can make the verifier accept a string y when in fact $y\not \in L$ except with some small probability.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The upper bound of this probability is referred to as the **soundness error** of a proof system.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] As long as the soundness error is bounded by a polynomial fraction of the potential running time of the verifier (i.e. $\epsilon \leq 1/\mathrm {poly} (|y|)$ ), it is always possible to amplify soundness until the soundness error becomes a negligible function of the running time of the verifier.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] This is achieved by repeating the proof and accepting only if all proofs verify.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] After $\ell$ repetitions, a soundness error $\epsilon$ will be reduced to $\epsilon ^{\ell }$ .
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The complexity class NP may be viewed as a very simple proof system.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In this system, the verifier is a deterministic, polynomial-time machine (a P machine).
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In the case where a valid proof certificate exists, the prover is always able to make the verifier accept by giving it that certificate.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In the case where there is no valid proof certificate, however, the input is not in the language, and no prover, however malicious it is, can convince the verifier otherwise, because any proof certificate will be rejected.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Although NP may be viewed as using interaction, it wasn't until 1985 that the concept of computation through interaction was conceived (in the context of complexity theory) by two independent groups of researchers.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] One approach, by László Babai, who published "Trading group theory for randomness", defined the *Arthur–Merlin* (**AM**) class hierarchy.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In this presentation, Arthur (the verifier) is a probabilistic, polynomial-time machine, while Merlin (the prover) has unbounded resources.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The class **MA** in particular is a simple generalization of the NP interaction above in which the verifier is probabilistic instead of deterministic.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] This machine is potentially more powerful than an ordinary NP interaction protocol, but the certificates are no less practical to verify, since **BPP** algorithms are considered as abstracting practical computation (see BPP).
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In a *public coin* protocol, the random choices made by the verifier are made public.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] They remain private in a private coin protocol.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In the same conference where Babai defined his proof system for **MA**, Shafi Goldwasser, Silvio Micali and Charles Rackoff published a paper defining the interactive proof system **IP**[*f*(*n*)].
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] This has the same machines as the **MA** protocol, except that *f*(*n*) *rounds* are allowed for an input of size *n*.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In each round, the verifier performs computation and passes a message to the prover, and the prover performs computation and passes information back to the verifier.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] At the end the verifier must make its decision.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] For example, in an **IP**[3] protocol, the sequence would be VPVPVPV, where V is a verifier turn and P is a prover turn.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In Arthur–Merlin protocols, Babai defined a similar class **AM**[*f*(*n*)], which allowed *f*(*n*) rounds, but he put one extra condition on the machine: the verifier must show the prover all the random bits it uses in its computation.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The result is that the verifier cannot "hide" anything from the prover, because the prover is powerful enough to simulate everything the verifier does if it knows what random bits it used.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] This is called a *public coin* protocol, because the random bits ("coin flips") are visible to both machines.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The **IP** approach is called a *private coin* protocol by contrast.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The essential problem with public coins is that if the prover wishes to maliciously convince the verifier to accept a string that is not in the language, it seems like the verifier might be able to thwart its plans if it can hide its internal state from it.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] This was a primary motivation in defining the **IP** proof systems.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In 1986, Goldwasser and Sipser showed, perhaps surprisingly, that the verifier's ability to hide coin flips from the prover does it little good after all, in that an Arthur–Merlin public coin protocol with only two more rounds can recognize all the same languages.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The result is that public-coin and private-coin protocols are roughly equivalent.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] To demonstrate the power of these classes, consider the graph isomorphism problem, the problem of determining whether it is possible to permute the vertices of one graph so that it is identical to another graph.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] This problem is in **NP**, since the proof certificate is the permutation that makes the graphs equal.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] It turns out that the complement of the graph isomorphism problem, a co-**NP** problem not known to be in **NP**, has an **AM** algorithm and the best way to see it is via a private coins algorithm.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Private coins may not be helpful, but more rounds of interaction are helpful.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] If we allow the probabilistic verifier machine and the all-powerful prover to interact for a polynomial number of rounds, we get the class of problems called **IP**.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In 1992, Adi Shamir revealed in one of the central results of complexity theory that **IP** equals **PSPACE**, the class of problems solvable by an ordinary deterministic Turing machine in polynomial space.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] If we allow the elements of the system to use quantum computation, the system is called a **quantum interactive proof system**, and the corresponding complexity class is called **QIP**.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] A series of results culminated in a 2010 breakthrough that **QIP** = **PSPACE**.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Not only can interactive proof systems solve problems not believed to be in **NP**, but under assumptions about the existence of one-way functions, a prover can convince the verifier of the solution without ever giving the verifier information about the solution.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] This is important when the verifier cannot be trusted with the full solution.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] At first it seems impossible that the verifier could be convinced that there is a solution when the verifier has not seen a certificate, but such proofs, known as zero-knowledge proofs are in fact believed to exist for all problems in **NP** and are valuable in cryptography.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Zero-knowledge proofs were first mentioned in the original 1985 paper on **IP** by Goldwasser, Micali and Rackoff for specific number-theoretic languages.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The extent of their power was however shown by Oded Goldreich, Silvio Micali and Avi Wigderson for all of **NP**, and this was first extended by Russell Impagliazzo and Moti Yung to all of **IP**.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] One goal of **IP'**s designers was to create the most powerful possible interactive proof system, and at first it seems like it cannot be made more powerful without making the verifier more powerful and so impractical.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Goldwasser et al. overcame this in their 1988 "Multi prover interactive proofs: How to remove intractability assumptions", which defines a variant of **IP** called **MIP** in which there are *two* independent provers.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] The two provers cannot communicate once the verifier has begun sending messages to them.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Just as it's easier to tell if a criminal is lying if he and his partner are interrogated in separate rooms, it's considerably easier to detect a malicious prover trying to trick the verifier into accepting a string not in the language if there is another prover it can double-check with.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] In fact, this is so helpful that Babai, Fortnow, and Lund were able to show that **MIP** = **NEXPTIME**, the class of all problems solvable by a nondeterministic machine in *exponential time*, a very large class.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] NEXPTIME contains PSPACE, and is believed to strictly contain PSPACE.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Adding a constant number of additional provers beyond two does not enable recognition of any more languages.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] This result paved the way for the celebrated PCP theorem, which can be considered to be a "scaled-down" version of this theorem.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] It is known that for any constant *k*, an MIP system with *k* provers and polynomially many rounds can be turned into an equivalent system with only 2 provers, and a constant number of rounds.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] While the designers of **IP** considered generalizations of Babai's interactive proof systems, others considered restrictions.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] A very useful interactive proof system is **PCP**(*f*(*n*), *g*(*n*)), which is a restriction of **MA** where Arthur can only use *f*(*n*) random bits and can only examine *g*(*n*) bits of the proof certificate sent by Merlin (essentially using random access).
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Furthermore, the PCP theorem asserts that the number of proof accesses can be brought all the way down to a constant.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] They used this valuable characterization of **NP** to prove that approximation algorithms do not exist for the optimization versions of certain NP-complete problems unless P = NP.
[src:interactive-proofs/interactive-proof-system] Such problems are now studied in the field known as hardness of approximation.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] In computational complexity theory, the class **IP** (which stands for **interactive proof**) is the class of problems solvable by an interactive proof system.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] The result was established in a series of papers: the first by Lund, Karloff, Fortnow, and Nisan showed that co-NP had multiple-prover interactive proofs; and the second, by Shamir, employed their technique to establish that IP=PSPACE.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] The result is a famous example where the proof does not relativize.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] The concept of an interactive proof system was first introduced by Shafi Goldwasser, Silvio Micali, and Charles Rackoff in 1985.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] An interactive proof system consists of two machines, a prover, *P*, which presents a proof that a given string *n* is a member of some language, and a verifier, *V*, that checks that the presented proof is correct.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] The prover is assumed to be infinite in computation and storage, while the verifier is a probabilistic polynomial-time machine with access to a random bit string whose length is polynomial on the size of *n*.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] These two machines exchange a polynomial number, *p*(*n*), of messages and once the interaction is completed, the verifier must decide whether or not *n* is in the language, with only a 1/3 chance of error.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] The Arthur–Merlin protocol, introduced by László Babai, is similar in nature, except that the number of rounds of interaction is bounded by a constant rather than a polynomial.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Goldwasser et al. have shown that *public-coin* protocols, where the random numbers used by the verifier are provided to the prover along with the challenges, are no less powerful than private-coin protocols.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] At most two additional rounds of interaction are required to replicate the effect of a private-coin protocol.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] The opposite inclusion is straightforward, because the verifier can always send to the prover the results of their private coin tosses, which proves that the two types of protocols are equivalent.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] The proof can be divided in two parts, we show that **IP** ⊆ **PSPACE** and **PSPACE** ⊆ **IP**.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] In order to demonstrate that **IP** ⊆ **PSPACE**, we present a simulation of an interactive proof system by a polynomial space machine.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] where Pr*r* is the probability taken over the random string *r* of length *p*.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] This expression is the average of *NMj+1*, weighted by the probability that the verifier sent message *mj+1*.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Take *M*0 to be the empty message sequence, here we will show that *NM0* can be computed in polynomial space, and that *NM0* = Pr[*V* accepts *w*].
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] First, to compute *NM0*, an algorithm can recursively calculate the values *NMj* for every *j* and *Mj*.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Since the depth of the recursion is *p*, only polynomial space is necessary.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] The second requirement is that we need *NM0* = Pr[*V* accepts *w*], the value needed to determine whether *w* is in A.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] We use induction to prove this as follows.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] We must show that for every 0 ≤ *j* ≤ *p* and every *Mj*, *NMj* = Pr[*V* accepts *w* starting at *Mj*], and we will do this using induction on *j*.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] The base case is to prove for *j* = *p*.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Then we will use induction to go from *p* down to 0.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] The base case of *j* = *p* is fairly simple.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Since *mp* is either accept or reject, if *mp* is accept, *NMp* is defined to be 1 and Pr[*V* accepts *w* starting at *Mj*] = 1 since the message stream indicates acceptance, thus the claim is true.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] If *mp* is reject, the argument is very similar.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] For the inductive step, we assume that for some *j*+1 ≤ *p* and any message sequence *Mj+1*, *NMj+1* = Pr[*V* accepts *w* starting at *Mj+1*] and then prove the hypothesis for *j* and any message sequence *Mj*.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] If *j* is even, *mj+1* is a message from *V* to *P*.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Finally, by definition, we can see that this is equal to Pr[*V* accepts *w* starting at *Mj*].
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] If *j* is odd, *mj+1* is a message from *P* to *V*.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] because the prover on the right-hand side could send the message *mj+1* to maximize the expression on the left-hand side.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Since the same Prover cannot do any better than send that same message.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Thus, this holds whether *i* is even or odd and the proof that **IP** ⊆ **PSPACE** is complete.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Here we have constructed a polynomial space machine that uses the best prover *P* for a particular string *w* in language *A*.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] We use this best prover in place of a prover with random input bits because we are able to try every set of random input bits in polynomial space.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Since we have simulated an interactive proof system with a polynomial space machine, we have shown that **IP** ⊆ **PSPACE**, as desired.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] In order to illustrate the technique that will be used to prove **PSPACE** ⊆ **IP**, we will first prove a weaker theorem, which was proven by Lund, et al.: #SAT ∈ **IP**.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Then using the concepts from this proof we will extend it to show that TQBF ∈ **IP**.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Note that this is different from the normal definition of #SAT, in that it is a decision problem, rather than a function.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] First we use arithmetization to map the Boolean formula with *n* variables, φ(*b*1, ..., *bn*) to a polynomial *p*φ(*x*1, ..., *xn*), where *p*φ mimics φ in that *p*φ is 1 if φ is true and 0 otherwise provided that the variables of *p*φ are assigned Boolean values.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] The Boolean operations ∨, ∧ and ¬ used in φ are simulated in *p*φ by replacing the operators in φ as shown in the table below.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] The operations *ab* and *a* ∗ *b* each result in a polynomial with a degree bounded by the sum of the degrees of the polynomials for *a* and *b* and hence, the degree of any variable is at most the length of φ.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Now let *F* be a finite field with order *q* > 2*n*; also demand that q be at least 1000.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Note that the value of *f*0 is the number of satisfying assignments of φ.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] *f*0 is a void function, with no variables.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Note that this is a public-coin algorithm.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] If φ has *k* satisfying assignments, clearly *V* will accept.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] If φ does not have *k* satisfying assignments we assume there is a prover ${\tilde {P}}$ that tries to convince *V* that φ does have *k* satisfying assignments.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] We show that this can only be done with low probability.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] To prevent *V* from rejecting in phase 0, ${\tilde {P}}$ has to send an incorrect value ${\tilde {f}}_{0}()$ to *P*.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] This is because a polynomial in a single variable of degree at most *d* can have no more than *d* roots (unless it always evaluates to 0).
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] So, any two polynomials in a single variable of degree at most *d* can be equal only in *d* places.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] There are *n* phases, so the probability that ${\tilde {P}}$ is lucky because *V* selects at some stage a convenient *ri* is at most 1/*n*.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] So, no prover can make the verifier accept with probability greater than 1/*n*.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] We can also see from the definition that the verifier *V* operates in probabilistic polynomial time.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] In order to show that **PSPACE** is a subset of **IP**, we need to choose a **PSPACE-complete** problem and show that it is in **IP**.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Once we show this, then it clear that **PSPACE** ⊆ **IP**.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] The proof technique demonstrated here is credited to Adi Shamir.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] We know that TQBF is in **PSPACE-Complete**.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Then *Qi* is a quantifier, either ∃ or ∀.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Now *fi* is the same as in the previous proof, but now it also includes quantifiers.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] By using the method described in #SAT, we must face a problem that for any *fi* the degree of the resulting polynomial may double with each quantifier.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] In order to prevent this, we must introduce a new reduction operator *R* which will reduce the degrees of the polynomial without changing their behavior on Boolean inputs.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Now for every *i* ≤ *k* we define the function *fi*.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] We also define $f_{k}(x_{1},\dots ,x_{m})$ to be the polynomial *p*(*x*1, ..., *xm*) which is obtained by arithmetizing φ.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Now we can see that the reduction operation R, doesn't change the degree of the polynomial.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Also it is important to see that the R*x* operation doesn't change the value of the function on Boolean inputs.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] So *f*0 is still the truth value of ψ, but the R*x* value produces a result that is linear in *x*.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Also after any ${\mathsf {Q}}_{i}x_{i}$ we add $\mathrm {R} _{x_{1}}\dots \mathrm {R} _{x_{i}}$ in ψ′ in order to reduce the degree down to 1 after arithmetizing ${\mathsf {Q}}_{i}$ .
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] If *n* is the length of ψ, all arithmetic operations in the protocol are over a field of size at least *n*4 where *n* is the length of ψ.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Goto phase *i* + 1 where *P* must persuade *V* that $f_{i}(r_{1},\dots ,r)$ is correct.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] This is the end of the protocol description.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] If ψ is true then *V* will accept when *P* follows the protocol.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Likewise if ${\tilde {P}}$ is a malicious prover which lies, and if ψ is false, then ${\tilde {P}}$ will need to lie at phase 0 and send some value for *f*0.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] The probability for ${\tilde {P}}$ to get lucky on some random *r* is at most the degree of the polynomial divided by the field size: $n/n^{4}$ .
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] The protocol runs through *O*(*n*2) phases, so the probability that ${\tilde {P}}$ gets lucky at some phase is ≤ 1/*n*.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] If ${\tilde {P}}$ is never lucky, then *V* will reject at phase *k*+1.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Since we have now shown that both **IP** ⊆ **PSPACE** and **PSPACE** ⊆ **IP**, we can conclude that **IP** = **PSPACE** as desired.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Moreover, we have shown that any **IP** algorithm may be taken to be public-coin, since the reduction from **PSPACE** to **IP** has this property.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] There are a number of variants of **IP** which slightly modify the definition of the interactive proof system.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] We summarize some of the better-known ones here.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] A subset of **IP** is the **deterministic Interactive Proof** class, which is similar to **IP** but has a deterministic verifier (i.e. with no randomness).
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] This seemingly stronger criterion of "perfect completeness" does not change the complexity class **IP**, since any language with an interactive proof system may be given an interactive proof system with perfect completeness.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] In 1988, Goldwasser et al. created an even more powerful interactive proof system based on **IP** called **MIP** in which there are *two* independent provers.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Just as it's easier to tell if a criminal is lying if he and his partner are interrogated in separate rooms, it's considerably easier to detect a malicious prover trying to trick the verifier if there is another prover it can double-check with.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Moreover, all languages in **NP** have zero-knowledge proofs in an **MIP** system, without any additional assumptions; this is only known for **IP** assuming the existence of one-way functions.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Although **IPP** also equals **PSPACE**, **IPP** protocols behaves quite differently from **IP** with respect to oracles: **IPP**=**PSPACE** with respect to all oracles, while **IP** ≠ **PSPACE** with respect to almost all oracles.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Essentially, this makes the prover a **BPP** machine with access to an oracle for the language, but only in the completeness case, not the soundness case.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] The concept is that if a language is in **compIP**, then interactively proving it is in some sense as easy as deciding it.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] With the oracle, the prover can easily solve the problem, but its limited power makes it much more difficult to convince the verifier of anything.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] In fact, **compIP** isn't even known or believed to contain **NP**.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] On the other hand, such a system can solve some problems believed to be hard.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Somewhat paradoxically, though such a system is not believed to be able to solve all of **NP**, it can easily solve all **NP-complete** problems due to self-reducibility.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] This stems from the fact that if the language L is not **NP**-hard, the prover is substantially limited in power (as it can no longer decide all **NP** problems with its oracle).
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Additionally, the graph nonisomorphism problem (which is a classical problem in **IP**) is also in **compIP**, since the only hard operation the prover has to do is isomorphism testing, which it can use the oracle to solve.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Quadratic non-residuosity and graph isomorphism are also in **compIP**.
[src:interactive-proofs/ip-complexity] Note, quadratic non-residuosity (QNR) is likely an easier problem than graph isomorphism as QNR is in **UP** intersect **co-UP**.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] In computational complexity theory, **PSPACE** is the set of all decision problems that can be solved by a Turing machine using a polynomial amount of space.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] It turns out that allowing the Turing machine to be nondeterministic does not add any extra power.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] Because of Savitch's theorem, ${\mathsf {NPSPACE}}$ is equivalent to ${\mathsf {PSPACE}}$ , because a deterministic Turing machine can simulate a nondeterministic Turing machine while roughly squaring the amount of space, and squaring takes polynomials to (bigger) polynomials.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] Also, the complements of all problems in ${\mathsf {PSPACE}}$ are also in ${\mathsf {PSPACE}}$ , meaning that ${\mathsf {coPSPACE}}={\mathsf {PSPACE}}$ .
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] From the third line, it follows that both in the first and in the second line, at least one of the set containments must be strict, but it is not known which.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] It is widely suspected that all are strict.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] The containments in the third line are both known to be strict.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] The first follows from direct diagonalization (the space hierarchy theorem, NL ⊂ NPSPACE) and the fact that PSPACE = NPSPACE via Savitch's theorem.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] The second follows simply from the space hierarchy theorem.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] The hardest problems in PSPACE are the PSPACE-complete problems.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] See PSPACE-complete for examples of problems that are suspected to be in PSPACE but not in NP.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] The class PSPACE is closed under operations union, complementation, and Kleene star.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] An alternative characterization of PSPACE is the set of problems decidable by an alternating Turing machine in polynomial time, sometimes called APTIME or just AP.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] A logical characterization of PSPACE from descriptive complexity theory is that it is the set of problems expressible in second-order logic with the addition of a transitive closure operator.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] A full transitive closure is not needed; a commutative transitive closure and even weaker forms suffice.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] It is the addition of this operator that (possibly) distinguishes PSPACE from PH.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] A major result of complexity theory is that PSPACE can be characterized as all the languages recognizable by a particular interactive proof system, the one defining the class IP.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] In this system, there is an all-powerful prover trying to convince a randomized polynomial-time verifier that a string is in the language.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] It should be able to convince the verifier with high probability if the string is in the language, but should not be able to convince it except with low probability if the string is not in the language.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] PSPACE can be characterized as the quantum complexity class QIP.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] PSPACE is also equal to PCTC, problems solvable by classical computers using closed timelike curves, as well as to BQPCTC, problems solvable by quantum computers using closed timelike curves.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] A language *B* is *PSPACE-complete* if it is in PSPACE and it is PSPACE-hard, which means for all *A* ∈ PSPACE, $A\leq _{\text{P}}B$ , where $A\leq _{\text{P}}B$ means that there is a polynomial-time many-one reduction from *A* to *B*.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] PSPACE-complete problems are of great importance to studying PSPACE problems because they represent the most difficult problems in PSPACE.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] Finding a simple solution to a PSPACE-complete problem would mean we have a simple solution to all other problems in PSPACE because all PSPACE problems could be reduced to a PSPACE-complete problem.
[src:interactive-proofs/pspace] An example of a PSPACE-complete problem is the quantified Boolean formula problem (usually abbreviated to **QBF** or **TQBF**; the **T** stands for "true").
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] In logic, soundness can refer to either a property of arguments or a property of formal deductive systems.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] These two properties are different but closely related.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] The former is more relevant for introductory deductive reasoning contexts and the latter arises in metalogic and mathematical logic.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] In deductive reasoning, a sound argument is an argument that is valid and all of its premises are true (and as a consequence its conclusion is true as well).
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] An argument is valid if, assuming its premises are true, the conclusion *must be* true.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Because of the logical necessity of the conclusion, this argument is valid; and because the argument is valid and its premises are true, the argument is sound.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] However, an argument can be valid without being sound.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] This argument is valid as the conclusion *must be* true assuming the premises are true.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Not all birds can fly (for example, Penguins).
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] For an argument to be sound, the argument must be valid *and* its premises must be true.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Some authors, such as Lemmon, have used the term "soundness" as synonymous with what is now meant by "validity", which left them with no particular word for what is now called "soundness".
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] But nowadays, this division of the terms is very widespread.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] In mathematical logic, a logical system has the soundness property if every formula that can be proved in the system is logically valid with respect to the semantics of the system.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] In most cases, this comes down to its rules having the property of *preserving truth*.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] The converse of soundness is known as completeness.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] In other words, a system is sound when all of its theorems are validities.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Soundness is among the most fundamental properties of mathematical logic.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] The soundness property provides the initial reason for counting a logical system as desirable.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] The completeness property means that every validity (truth) is provable.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Together they imply that all and only validities are provable.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] For example, in an axiomatic system, proof of soundness amounts to verifying the validity of the axioms and that the rules of inference preserve validity (or the weaker property, truth).
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] If the system allows Hilbert-style deduction, it requires only verifying the validity of the axioms and one rule of inference, namely modus ponens (and sometimes substitution).
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Soundness properties come in two main varieties: weak and strong soundness, of which the former is a restricted form of the latter.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Strong soundness is the definition given earlier in this section and weak soundness restricts this to sentences which are provable from no premises, i.e., when there are no sentences to the right of the turnstiles.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Weak soundness of a deductive system is the property that any sentence that is provable *from no premises* in that deductive system is also true on all interpretations or structures of the semantic theory for the language upon which that theory is based.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Symbolically we write, if $\vdash C$ then $\vDash C$ .
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Some writers will explicitly include the empty set, giving if $\emptyset \vdash C$ then $\emptyset \models C$ .
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Using the narrow definition of theorem, for sentences provable from no premises, weak soundness says that all theorems are tautologies.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Strong soundness of a deductive system is the property that any sentence C that is provable from a (possibly empty) set of premises/sentences $\Gamma =\{A_{1},A_{2},...,A_{n}\}$ is also a semantic consequence of that set, i.e., C is true in any model that makes all members of $\Gamma$ .
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Symbolically we write, if $\Gamma \vdash C$ , then $\Gamma \models C$ .
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Notice that when $\Gamma$ is empty, we have the statement of weak soundness.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] If *T* is a theory whose objects of discourse can be interpreted as natural numbers, we say *T* is *arithmetically sound* if all theorems of *T* are actually true about the standard mathematical integers.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] For further information, see ω-consistent theory.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] The converse of the soundness property is the completeness property.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] A deductive system with a semantic theory is strongly complete if every sentence C that is a semantic consequence of a set of sentences $\Gamma$ can be derived in the deduction system from that set.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] In symbols: if $\Gamma \models C$ then $\Gamma \vdash C$ .
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Completeness of first-order logic was first explicitly established by Gödel, though some of the main results were contained in earlier work of Skolem.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Informally, a soundness theorem for a deductive system expresses that all provable sentences are true.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Completeness states that all true sentences are provable.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Gödel's first incompleteness theorem shows that for languages sufficient for doing a certain amount of arithmetic, there can be no consistent and effective deductive system that is complete with respect to the intended interpretation of the symbolism of that language.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] Thus, not all sound deductive systems are complete in this special sense of completeness, in which the class of models (up to isomorphism) is restricted to the intended one.
[src:interactive-proofs/soundness] The original completeness proof applies to *all* classical models, not some special proper subclass of intended ones.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The intuition behind the nontriviality of zero-knowledge proofs is that it is trivial to prove possession of the relevant information simply by revealing it; the hard part is to prove this possession without revealing this information (or any aspect of it whatsoever).
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Zero-knowledge proofs can be interactive, meaning that the prover and verifier exchange messages according to some protocol, or noninteractive, meaning that the verifier is convinced by a single prover message and no other communication is needed.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In the standard model, interaction is required, except for trivial proofs of BPP problems.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In the common random string and random oracle models, non-interactive zero-knowledge proofs exist.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The Fiat–Shamir heuristic can be used to transform certain interactive zero-knowledge proofs into noninteractive ones.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] One example of a math-free zero-knowledge proof is if Peggy wants to prove to Victor that she has drawn a red card from a standard deck of 52 playing cards, without revealing which specific red card she holds.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Victor observes Peggy draw a card at random from the shuffled deck, but she keeps the card face-down so he cannot see it.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] To prove her card is red without revealing its identity, Peggy takes the remaining 51 cards from the deck and systematically shows Victor all 26 black cards (the 13 spades and 13 clubs) one by one, placing them face-up on the table.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Since a standard deck contains exactly 26 red cards and 26 black cards, and Peggy has demonstrated that all the black cards remain in the deck, Victor can conclude with certainty that Peggy's hidden card must be red.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This proof is zero-knowledge because Victor learns only that Peggy's card is red, but gains no information about whether it is a heart or diamond, or which specific red card she holds.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The proof would be equally convincing whether Peggy held the Ace of Hearts or the Two of Diamonds.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Furthermore, even if the interaction were recorded, the recording would not reveal Peggy's specific card to future observers, maintaining the zero-knowledge property.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If Peggy were lying and actually held a black card, she would be unable to produce all 26 black cards from the remaining deck, making deception impossible.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This demonstrates the soundness of the proof system.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This type of physical zero-knowledge proof using standard playing cards belongs to a broader class of card-based cryptographic protocols that allow participants to perform secure computations using everyday objects.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Another well-known example of a zero-knowledge proof is the "Where's Waldo" example.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In this example, the prover has a page from a *Where's Waldo?* children's book, which shows many hundreds of cartoon people, where only one of them is the visually distinctive character of Waldo.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The prover wants to prove to the verifier that they know where Waldo is on the page, without revealing his location to the verifier.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The prover starts by taking a large black board with a small hole in it, the size of Waldo.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The board is twice the size of the book in both directions, so the verifier cannot see where on the page the prover is placing it.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The prover then places the board over the page so that Waldo is in the hole.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The verifier can now look through the hole and see Waldo, but cannot see any other part of the page.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Therefore, the prover has proven to the verifier that they know where Waldo is, without revealing any other information about his location.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This example is not a perfect zero-knowledge proof, because the prover does reveal some information about Waldo's location, such as his body position.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] However, it is a decent illustration of the basic concept of a zero-knowledge proof.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy takes either path A or B, while Victor waits outside.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy reliably appears at the exit Victor names.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] There is a well-known story presenting the fundamental ideas of zero-knowledge proofs, first published in 1990 by Jean-Jacques Quisquater and others in their paper "How to Explain Zero-Knowledge Protocols to Your Children".
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The two parties in the zero-knowledge proof story are Peggy as the prover of the statement, and Victor, the verifier of the statement.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In this story, Peggy has uncovered the secret word used to open a magic door in a cave.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The cave is shaped like a ring, with the entrance on one side and the magic door blocking the opposite side.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Victor wants to know whether Peggy knows the secret word; but Peggy, being a very private person, does not want to reveal her knowledge (the secret word) to Victor or to reveal the fact of her knowledge to the world in general.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] They label the paths from the entrance A and B.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] First, Victor waits outside the cave as Peggy goes in.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy takes either path A or B; Victor is not allowed to see which path she takes.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Then, Victor enters the cave and shouts the name of the path he wants her to use to return, either A or B, chosen at random.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Providing she really does know the magic word, this is easy: she opens the door, if necessary, and returns along the desired path.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] However, suppose she did not know the word.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Then, she would only be able to return by the named path if Victor were to give the name of the same path by which she had entered.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Since Victor would choose A or B at random, she would have a 50% chance of guessing correctly.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If they were to repeat this trick many times, say 20 times in a row, her chance of successfully anticipating all of Victor's requests would be reduced to 1 in 220, or 9.54 × 10−7.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Thus, if Peggy repeatedly appears at the exit Victor names, then he can conclude that it is extremely probable that Peggy does, in fact, know the secret word.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] With respect to third-party observers: even if Victor is wearing a hidden camera that records the whole transaction, the only thing the camera will record is in one case Victor shouting "A!" and Peggy appearing at A or in the other case Victor shouting "B!" and Peggy appearing at B.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A recording of this type would be trivial for any two people to fake (requiring only that Peggy and Victor agree beforehand on the sequence of As and Bs that Victor will shout).
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Such a recording will certainly never be convincing to anyone but the original participants.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In fact, even a person who was present as an observer at the original experiment should be unconvinced, since Victor and Peggy could have orchestrated the whole "experiment" from start to finish.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Further, if Victor chooses his As and Bs by flipping a coin on-camera, this protocol loses its zero-knowledge property; the on-camera coin flip would probably be convincing to any person watching the recording later.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Thus, although this does not reveal the secret word to Victor, it does make it possible for Victor to convince the world in general that Peggy has that knowledge—counter to Peggy's stated wishes.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] However, digital cryptography generally "flips coins" by relying on a pseudo-random number generator, which is akin to a coin with a fixed pattern of heads and tails known only to the coin's owner.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If Victor's coin behaved this way, then again it would be possible for Victor and Peggy to have faked the experiment, so using a pseudo-random number generator would not reveal Peggy's knowledge to the world in the same way that using a flipped coin would.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy could prove to Victor that she knows the magic word, without revealing it to him, in a single trial.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If both Victor and Peggy go together to the mouth of the cave, Victor can watch Peggy go in through A and come out through B.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This would prove with certainty that Peggy knows the magic word, without revealing the magic word to Victor.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] However, such a proof could be observed by a third party, or recorded by Victor and such a proof would be convincing to anybody.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In other words, Peggy could not refute such proof by claiming she colluded with Victor, and she is therefore no longer in control of who is aware of her knowledge.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Imagine Victor is red-green color-blind (while Peggy is not) and Peggy has two balls: one red and one green, but otherwise identical.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] To Victor, the balls seem completely identical.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Victor is skeptical that the balls are actually distinguishable.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy wants to *prove to Victor that the balls are in fact differently colored*, but nothing else.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In particular, Peggy does not want to reveal which ball is the red one and which is the green.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Here is the proof system: Peggy gives the two balls to Victor and he puts them behind his back.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Next, he takes one of the balls and brings it out from behind his back and displays it.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] He then places it behind his back again and then chooses to reveal just one of the two balls, picking one of the two at random with equal probability.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] He will ask Peggy, "Did I switch the ball?" This whole procedure is then repeated as often as necessary.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] By looking at the balls' colors, Peggy can, of course, say with certainty whether or not he switched them.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] On the other hand, if the balls were the same color and hence indistinguishable, Peggy's ability to determine whether a switch occurred would be no better than random guessing.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Since the probability that Peggy would have randomly succeeded at identifying each switch/non-switch is 50%, the probability of having randomly succeeded at *all* switch/non-switches approaches zero.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Over multiple trials, the success rate would statistically converge to 50%, and Peggy could not achieve a performance significantly better than chance.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If Peggy and Victor repeat this "proof" multiple times (e.g.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] 20 times), Victor should become convinced that the balls are indeed differently colored.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The above proof is *zero-knowledge* because Victor never learns which ball is green and which is red; indeed, he gains no knowledge about how to distinguish the balls.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] **Soundness**: if the statement is false, then no cheating prover can convince an honest verifier that it is true, except with some small probability.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] **Zero-knowledge**: if the statement is true, then no verifier learns anything other than the fact that the statement is true.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In other words, just knowing the statement (not the secret) is sufficient to imagine a scenario showing that the prover knows the secret.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This is formalized by showing that every verifier has some *simulator* that, given only the statement to be proved (and no access to the prover), can produce a transcript that "looks like" an interaction between an honest prover and the verifier in question.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The first two of these are properties of more general interactive proof systems.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The third is what makes the proof zero-knowledge.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Zero-knowledge proofs are not proofs in the mathematical sense of the term because there is some small probability, the *soundness error*, that a cheating prover will be able to convince the verifier of a false statement.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In other words, zero-knowledge proofs are probabilistic "proofs" rather than deterministic proofs.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] However, there are techniques to decrease the soundness error to negligibly small values (for example, guessing correctly on a hundred or thousand binary decisions has a 1/2100 or 1/21000 soundness error, respectively.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] As the number of bits increases, the soundness error decreases toward zero).
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A formal definition of zero-knowledge must use some computational model, the most common one being that of a Turing machine.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The prover P is modeled as having unlimited computation power (in practice, P usually is a probabilistic Turing machine).
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Intuitively, the definition states that an interactive proof system (*P*,*V*) is zero-knowledge if for any verifier ${\hat {V}}$ there exists an efficient simulator S (depending on ${\hat {V}}$ ) that can reproduce the conversation between P and ${\hat {V}}$ on any given input.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The auxiliary string z in the definition plays the role of "prior knowledge" (including the random coins of ${\hat {V}}$ ).
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The definition implies that ${\hat {V}}$ cannot use any prior knowledge string z to mine information out of its conversation with P, because if S is also given this prior knowledge then it can reproduce the conversation between ${\hat {V}}$ and P just as before.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The definition given is that of perfect zero-knowledge.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Computational zero-knowledge is obtained by requiring that the views of the verifier ${\hat {V}}$ and the simulator are only computationally indistinguishable, given the auxiliary string.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] These ideas can be applied to a more realistic cryptography application.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy wants to prove to Victor that she knows the discrete logarithm of a given value in a given group.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] For example, given a value y, a large prime p, and a generator g , she wants to prove that she knows a value x such that *g**x* ≡ *y* (mod *p*), without revealing x.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The protocol proceeds as follows: in each round, Peggy generates a random number r, computes *C* = *g**r* mod *p* and discloses this to Victor.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] After receiving C, Victor randomly issues one of the following two requests: he either requests that Peggy discloses the value of r, or the value of (*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1).
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Victor can verify either answer; if he requested r, he can then compute *g**r* mod *p* and verify that it matches C.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If he requested (*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1), then he can verify that C is consistent with this, by computing *g*(*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1) mod *p* and verifying that it matches (*C* · *y*) mod *p*.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If Peggy indeed knows the value of x, then she can respond to either one of Victor's possible challenges.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] On the other hand, if she knows that Victor will request (*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1), then she picks a random value *r*′, computes *C*′ ≡ *g**r*′ · (*g**x*)−1 mod *p*, and discloses *C*′ to Victor as the value of C that he is expecting.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] When Victor challenges her to reveal (*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1), she reveals *r*′, for which Victor will verify consistency, since he will in turn compute *g**r*′ mod *p*, which matches *C*′ · *y*, since Peggy multiplied by the modular multiplicative inverse of y.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] However, if in either one of the above scenarios Victor issues a challenge other than the one she was expecting and for which she manufactured the result, then she will be unable to respond to the challenge under the assumption of infeasibility of solving the discrete log for this group.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If she picked r and disclosed *C* = *g**r* mod *p*, then she will be unable to produce a valid (*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1) that would pass Victor's verification, given that she does not know x.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Thus, a cheating prover has a 0.5 probability of successfully cheating in one round.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] By executing a large-enough number of rounds, the probability of a cheating prover succeeding can be made arbitrarily low.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] To show that the above interactive proof gives zero knowledge other than the fact that Peggy knows x, one can use similar arguments as used in the above proof of completeness and soundness.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Specifically, a simulator, say Simon, who does not know x, can simulate the exchange between Peggy and Victor by the following procedure.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Firstly, Simon randomly flips a fair coin.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If the result is "heads", then he picks a random value r, computes *C* = *g**r* mod *p*, and discloses C as if it is a message from Peggy to Victor.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Then Simon also outputs a message "request the value of r" as if it is sent from Victor to Peggy, and immediately outputs the value of r as if it is sent from Peggy to Victor.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] On the other hand, if the coin flipping result is "tails", then Simon picks a random number *r*′, computes *C*′ = *g**r*′ · *y*−1 mod *p*, and discloses *C*′ as if it is a message from Peggy to Victor.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Then Simon outputs "request the value of (*x* + *r*) mod (*p* − 1)" as if it is a message from Victor to Peggy.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Finally, Simon outputs the value of *r*′ as if it is the response from Peggy back to Victor.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] By the previous arguments when proving the completeness and soundness, the interactive communication simulated by Simon is indistinguishable from the true correspondence between Peggy and Victor.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The zero-knowledge property is thus guaranteed.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The following scheme is due to Manuel Blum.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In this scenario, Peggy knows a Hamiltonian cycle for a large graph G.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Victor knows G but not the cycle (e.g., Peggy has generated G and revealed it to him.) Finding a Hamiltonian cycle given a large graph is believed to be computationally infeasible, since its corresponding decision version is known to be NP-complete.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy will prove that she knows the cycle without simply revealing it (perhaps Victor is interested in buying it but wants verification first, or maybe Peggy is the only one who knows this information and is proving her identity to Victor).
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] It is important that the commitment to the graph be such that Victor can verify, in the second case, that the cycle is really made of edges from H.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This can be done by, for example, committing to every edge (or lack thereof) separately.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If Peggy does know a Hamiltonian cycle in G, then she can easily satisfy Victor's demand for either the graph isomorphism producing H from G (which she had committed to in the first step) or a Hamiltonian cycle in H (which she can construct by applying the isomorphism to the cycle in G).
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Peggy's answers do not reveal the original Hamiltonian cycle in G.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In each round, Victor will learn only H's isomorphism to G or a Hamiltonian cycle in H.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] He would need both answers for a single H to discover the cycle in G, so the information remains unknown as long as Peggy can generate a distinct H every round.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If Peggy does not know of a Hamiltonian cycle in G, but somehow knew in advance what Victor would ask to see each round, then she could cheat.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] For example, if Peggy knew ahead of time that Victor would ask to see the Hamiltonian cycle in H, then she could generate a Hamiltonian cycle for an unrelated graph.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Similarly, if Peggy knew in advance that Victor would ask to see the isomorphism then she could simply generate an isomorphic graph H (in which she also does not know a Hamiltonian cycle).
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Victor could simulate the protocol by himself (without Peggy) because he knows what he will ask to see.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Therefore, Victor gains no information about the Hamiltonian cycle in G from the information revealed in each round.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If Peggy does not know the information, then she can guess which question Victor will ask and generate either a graph isomorphic to G or a Hamiltonian cycle for an unrelated graph, but since she does not know a Hamiltonian cycle for G, she cannot do both.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] With this guesswork, her chance of fooling Victor is 2−*n*, where n is the number of rounds.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] For all realistic purposes, it is infeasibly difficult to defeat a zero-knowledge proof with a reasonable number of rounds in this way.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Zero-knowledge proof schemes can be constructed from various cryptographic primitives, such as hash-based cryptography, pairing-based cryptography, multi-party computation, or lattice-based cryptography.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Generally, zero-knowledge proofs are used within protocols to enforce honest behavior while maintaining privacy.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Roughly, the idea is to force a user to prove, using a zero-knowledge proof, that their behavior is correct according to the protocol.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Research in zero-knowledge proofs has been motivated by authentication systems where one party wants to prove its identity to a second party via some secret information (such as a password) but does not want the second party to learn anything about this secret.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This is called a "zero-knowledge proof of knowledge".
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] However, a password is typically too small or insufficiently random to be used in many schemes for zero-knowledge proofs of knowledge.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A zero-knowledge password proof is a special kind of zero-knowledge proof of knowledge that addresses the limited size of passwords.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In April 2015, the one-out-of-many proofs protocol (a Sigma protocol) was introduced.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In August 2021, Cloudflare, an American web infrastructure and security company, decided to use the one-out-of-many proofs mechanism for private web verification using vendor hardware.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] In 2016, the Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory and Princeton University demonstrated a technique that may have applicability to future nuclear disarmament talks.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] It would allow inspectors to confirm whether or not an object is indeed a nuclear weapon without recording, sharing, or revealing the internal workings, which might be secret.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Zero-knowledge proofs were applied in the Zerocoin and Zerocash protocols, which culminated in the birth of Zcoin (later rebranded as Firo in 2020) and Zcash cryptocurrencies in 2016.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Zerocoin has a built-in mixing model that does not trust any peers or centralized mixing providers to ensure anonymity.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Users can transact in a base currency and can cycle the currency into and out of Zerocoins.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The Zerocash protocol uses a similar model (a variant known as a non-interactive zero-knowledge proof) except that it can obscure the transaction amount, while Zerocoin cannot.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Bulletproofs are an improvement from non-interactive zero-knowledge proofs where a trusted setup is not needed.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Because of asymmetric signatures in documents such as passports and emails, zero knowledge proofs can be made of people's identities in order to privately verify information about themselves.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] For instance, you can prove that you are over 18 to a website, without revealing other details like your exact name or country of origin, by proving in zero knowledge that you own a passport signed by a valid government key for an age value over 18.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] By similarly making zero-knowledge proofs of the DKIM signatures of their emails, people can prove that they ordered or transferred a domain or concert ticket, own some handle on a social media service, or ordered something on an e-commerce service.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The zero knowledge property allows people to keep their own identity and email address private while doing so.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] These can be used to enable private and fair elections, low-fee secondary marketplaces, and whistleblowing services.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A related line of work applies zero-knowledge proofs to database analytics via so-called zero-knowledge "coprocessors": off-chain systems that execute queries and return both the result and a proof that the computation was performed correctly on untampered data.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Academic prototypes have shown how to produce ZK proofs for ad-hoc SQL queries while hiding inputs and guaranteeing correctness of the result (e.g., ZKSQL).
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Zero-knowledge proofs were first conceived in 1985 by Shafi Goldwasser, Silvio Micali, and Charles Rackoff in their paper "The Knowledge Complexity of Interactive Proof-Systems".
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This paper introduced the IP hierarchy of interactive proof systems (*see interactive proof system*) and conceived the concept of *knowledge complexity*, a measurement of the amount of knowledge about the proof transferred from the prover to the verifier.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] They also gave the first zero-knowledge proof for a concrete problem, that of deciding quadratic nonresidues mod *m*.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Together with a paper by László Babai and Shlomo Moran, this landmark paper invented interactive proof systems, for which all five authors won the first Gödel Prize in 1993.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The quadratic nonresidue problem has both an NP and a co-NP algorithm, and so lies in the intersection of NP and co-NP.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This was also true of several other problems for which zero-knowledge proofs were subsequently discovered, such as an unpublished proof system by Oded Goldreich verifying that a two-prime modulus is not a Blum integer.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Oded Goldreich, Silvio Micali, and Avi Wigderson took this one step further, showing that, assuming the existence of unbreakable encryption, one can create a zero-knowledge proof system for the NP-complete graph coloring problem with three colors.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Since every problem in NP can be efficiently reduced to this problem, this means that, under this assumption, all problems in NP have zero-knowledge proofs.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The reason for the assumption is that, as in the above example, their protocols require encryption.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A commonly cited sufficient condition for the existence of unbreakable encryption is the existence of one-way functions, but it is conceivable that some physical means might also achieve it.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] On top of this, they also showed that the graph nonisomorphism problem, the complement of the graph isomorphism problem, has a zero-knowledge proof.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] This problem is in co-NP, but is not currently known to be in either NP or any practical class.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Not liking to make unnecessary assumptions, many theorists sought a way to eliminate the necessity of one way functions.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] One way this was done was with *multi-prover interactive proof systems* (see interactive proof system), which have multiple independent provers instead of only one, allowing the verifier to "cross-examine" the provers in isolation to avoid being misled.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] It can be shown that, without any intractability assumptions, all languages in NP have zero-knowledge proofs in such a system.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] It turns out that, in an Internet-like setting, where multiple protocols may be executed concurrently, building zero-knowledge proofs is more challenging.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The line of research investigating concurrent zero-knowledge proofs was initiated by the work of Dwork, Naor, and Sahai.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] One particular development along these lines has been the development of witness-indistinguishable proof protocols.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] The property of witness-indistinguishability is related to that of zero-knowledge, yet witness-indistinguishable protocols do not suffer from the same problems of concurrent execution.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Another variant of zero-knowledge proofs are non-interactive zero-knowledge proofs.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Blum, Feldman, and Micali showed that a common random string shared between the prover and the verifier is enough to achieve computational zero-knowledge without requiring interaction.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A list of zero-knowledge proof protocols and libraries is provided below along with comparisons based on *transparency*, *universality*, *plausible post-quantum security*, and *programming paradigm*.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A transparent protocol is one that does not require any trusted setup and uses public randomness.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A universal protocol is one that does not require a separate trusted setup for each circuit.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Finally, a plausibly post-quantum protocol is one that is not susceptible to known attacks involving quantum algorithms.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] While zero-knowledge proofs offer a secure way to verify information, the arithmetic circuits that implement them must be carefully designed.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] If these circuits lack sufficient constraints, they may introduce subtle yet critical security vulnerabilities.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] One of the most common classes of vulnerabilities in these systems is under-constrained logic, where insufficient constraints allow a malicious prover to produce a proof for an incorrect statement that still passes verification.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A 2024 systematization of known attacks found that approximately 96% of documented circuit-layer bugs in SNARK-based systems were due to under-constrained circuits.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] These vulnerabilities often arise during the translation of high-level logic into low-level constraint systems, particularly when using domain-specific languages such as Circom or Gnark.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Recent research has demonstrated that formally proving determinism – ensuring that a circuit's outputs are uniquely determined by its inputs – can eliminate entire classes of these vulnerabilities.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Zero-knowledge virtual machines (zkVMs) are general-purpose virtual computers designed to execute code and generate zero-knowledge proofs that verify off-chain, without revealing private inputs, that the code ran correctly and produced the claimed result.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] A proof is a compact, structured binary file that can be efficiently checked by anyone using the zkVM's verifier tool without re-running the original computation.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] zkVMs have both development and security benefits.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Using a zkVM, developers can execute and verify complex computations off-chain, avoiding high on-chain "gas costs" (blockchain processing fees) and maintaining the privacy of code or data.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Several recently developed zkVMs, such as those developed by RISC Zero and Succinct Labs, support the RISC-V instruction set, which allows programmers to write code in mainstream programming languages like Rust instead of using a domain-specific circuit language such as Circom.
[src:interactive-proofs/zero-knowledge-proof] Other zkVMs take different approaches, targeting WebAssembly (WASM) or implementing custom instruction sets optimized for zero-knowledge performance or integration with particular blockchain environments.
